85 Sì come neve tra le vive travi 86 per lo dosso d’Italia si congela, 87 soffiata e stretta da li venti schiavi,
88 poi, liquefatta, in sé stessa trapela, 89 pur che la terra che perde ombra spiri, 90 sì che par foco fonder la candela;
91 così fui sanza lagrime e sospiri 92 anzi ’l cantar di quei che notan sempre 93 dietro a le note de li etterni giri;
94 ma poi che ’ntesi ne le dolci tempre 95 lor compatire a me, par che se detto 96 avesser: ‘Donna, perché sì lo stempre?’,
97 lo gel che m’era intorno al cor ristretto, 98 spirito e acqua fessi, e con angoscia 99 de la bocca e de li occhi uscì del petto.

query.result:
85 As snow among the living timbers 86 over the spine of Italy freezes, 87 blown and constricted by the slave winds,
88 then, liquefied, leaks into itself, 89 provided that the earth that loses shadow breathes, 90 so that it seems fire melts the candle;
91 thus I was without tears and sighs 92 except the singing of those who always note 93 behind the notes of the eternal revolutions;
94 but after I heard in the sweet temples 95 their compassion for me, it seems that they had said: 96 ‘Lady, why do you so diminish it?’,
97 the ice that was around my heart constricted, 98 spirit and water made, and with anguish 99 from the mouth and from the eyes exited the breast.

100 She, still firm on the said thigh 101 of the chariot standing, to the pious substances 102 turned her words thus afterwards:
103 “You watch in the eternal day, 104 so that night nor sleep steals from you 105 step that makes the world through its ways;
106 whence my response is with more care 107 that he understands who from there weeps, 108 because there may be guilt and pain of one measure.”

